{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T18:53:34.579131+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 56 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 69 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":69,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":56,"completed_with_unit_data":56,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":18,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2559,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 56 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -25.6%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":420,"p25":-0.4823,"median":-0.2559,"p75":-0.0176},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.1014,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 56 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +10.1%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":56,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":56,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.0927,"mean":0.1317,"median":0.1014,"p25":-0.1001,"p50":0.1014,"p75":0.277,"p10":-0.1916,"p90":0.5261},"median_actual_dollars":234119.97},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~119 hours per plumbing unit","value":118.7163,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 118.7 hrs/unit (P25 101, P75 143). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 101 and 143 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":56,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":164.9506,"median":118.7163,"p25":100.5151,"p50":118.7163,"p75":142.7733,"p10":74.9104,"p90":167.6476,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 38.4%","value":0.384,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 38.4%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":56,"p25":0.3128,"median":0.384,"p75":0.4524},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$41.27/hr (1.42\u00d7 blended)","value":41.2698,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $41.27/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.42\u00d7 means OWP carries ~42% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":28.7662,"loaded_wage_median":41.2698,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4241},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.5% median)","value":-0.155,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.5%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":532,"min":-0.9914,"max":3.4135,"mean":-0.0945,"median":-0.155,"p25":-0.411,"p50":-0.155,"p75":0.1064,"p10":-0.5939,"p90":0.4421},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":56,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":164.9506,"median":118.7163,"p25":100.5151,"p50":118.7163,"p75":142.7733,"p10":74.9104,"p90":167.6476,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":56,"min":1419.3979,"max":90082.0,"mean":5169.8002,"median":3614.8673,"p25":2707.6554,"p50":3614.8673,"p75":4217.5041,"p10":1960.7734,"p90":5091.2357,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":56,"min":1219.6971,"max":58415.81,"mean":4570.3443,"median":3495.1866,"p25":2864.4666,"p50":3495.1866,"p75":4164.4393,"p10":2061.6333,"p90":4985.2161,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":56,"min":7181.5,"max":350295.0,"mean":21305.0145,"median":15766.1759,"p25":12286.7774,"p50":15766.1759,"p75":17508.5409,"p10":10036.2182,"p90":19129.495,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":56,"min":0.1089,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2365,"median":0.2312,"p25":0.2105,"p50":0.2312,"p75":0.2727,"p10":0.1873,"p90":0.2904,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":56,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3135,"mean":0.2337,"median":0.2348,"p25":0.2158,"p50":0.2348,"p75